        <marginalia anchor_text="vse none other flesh but rosted or sodde" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>At Statius de Tideo Homerico: Maior in exiguo regnabat corpore Virtus: et nuper in Italia N Piccininus,
                        Bellator erat omniu[m] acerrimus, Duxq[ue] maximè terribilis: qui tame[n] ea fuit corporis paruitate, vt sacculo impositus aliquandò
                        euaderet, tanq[uam] sarcinula aliqua à milite abreptus.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Publius Papinius Statius"/>
                    <person name="Tydeus"/>
                    <person name="Homer"/>
                    <person name="Nicholas Piccininus"/>
                    <book title="Thebaid"/>
                    <location name="Italy"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>But Statius on the Homeric Tydeus: "Greater strength reigned in a small body": and recently in Italy,
            Nicholas Piccininus. The fighter was the most severe of all, and the general was especially frightful: 
            who nevertheless had such a small body that, he would sometimes escape being placed in a small bag, as if being snatched away by a soldier with some small pack.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
